Install a web server on a Linux system. Install and configure Snort as IDS on this system.  Add following rules to Snort to generate an alert for following threats.
If a ping packet with size grater than 128 bytes is received.
If from an outside IP address 30 ICMP packets are received within 1 min.
If from an outside single IP address more that 20 TCP SYN requests are received in 1 min to the web server
If a brute force attack is done on the SSH service.
If a Kali Linux machine boots in the network.
If gmail website is accessed from the web server.
If facebook website is accessed from the web server.
If instagram website is accessed from the web server.
----------------------
sudo apt update
sudo apt install snort -y


Since the question specifically says:

> **Install a web server on a Linux system. Install and configure Snort as IDS on this system.**

This means **Snort must run on the Ubuntu Web Server itself**, not on pfSense.

Your topology should be:

```text
Internet / Bridged Network (192.168.74.0/24)
        |
        |
 Ubuntu Web Server + Snort IDS
        |
    192.168.74.X
```

or

```text
Kali Linux        --->      Ubuntu Web Server + Snort
192.168.74.20              192.168.74.10
```

---

# 1. Verify Network

## Ubuntu Web Server

Example:

```bash
ip addr
```

Output:

```text
192.168.74.10/24
```

---

## Kali

Example:

```text
192.168.74.20/24
```

---

# 2. Install Apache Web Server

```bash
sudo apt update

sudo apt install apache2 -y
```

Enable service:

```bash
sudo systemctl enable apache2
sudo systemctl start apache2
```

Verify:

```bash
systemctl status apache2
```

Open browser:

```text
http://192.168.74.10
```

Apache page should appear.

---

# 3. Install Snort

Verify:

```bash
snort -V
```

Expected:

```text
Version 2.9.x
```

---

# 4. Find Interface Name

```bash
ip a
```

Example:

```text
ens33
```

Remember this interface.

---

# 5. Configure snort.conf

Open:

```bash
sudo nano /etc/snort/snort.conf
```

---

## HOME_NET

Find:

```text
ipvar HOME_NET any
```

Replace:

```text
ipvar HOME_NET 192.168.74.0/24
```

---

## EXTERNAL_NET

Find:

```text
ipvar EXTERNAL_NET any
```

Replace:

```text
ipvar EXTERNAL_NET !$HOME_NET
```

---

## Include Local Rules

At bottom verify:

```text
include $RULE_PATH/local.rules
```

If missing add:

```text
include $RULE_PATH/local.rules
```

Save.

---

# 6. Create local.rules

Open:

```bash
sudo nano /etc/snort/rules/local.rules
```

Paste everything below.

---

# Rule 1

## Ping >128 Bytes

```snort
alert icmp any any -> $HOME_NET any \
(msg:"ICMP Packet >128 Bytes"; \
dsize:>128; \
sid:1000001; rev:1;)
```

---

# Rule 2

## 30 ICMP Packets In 1 Minute

```snort
alert icmp $EXTERNAL_NET any -> $HOME_NET any \
(msg:"ICMP Flood Detected"; \
detection_filter:track by_src,count 30,seconds 60; \
sid:1000002; rev:1;)
```

---

# Rule 3

## More Than 20 SYN Requests To Web Server

Ubuntu Web Server:

```text
192.168.74.10
```

Rule:

```snort
alert tcp $EXTERNAL_NET any -> 192.168.74.10 80 \
(msg:"SYN Flood Against Web Server"; \
flags:S; \
detection_filter:track by_src,count 20,seconds 60; \
sid:1000003; rev:1;)
```

---

# Rule 4

## SSH Brute Force

```snort
alert tcp $EXTERNAL_NET any -> 192.168.74.10 22 \
(msg:"SSH Brute Force Attack"; \
flags:S; \
detection_filter:track by_src,count 10,seconds 60; \
sid:1000004; rev:1;)
```

---

# Rule 5

## Kali Linux Boot Detection

Detect DHCP hostname "kali"

```snort
alert udp any 68 -> any 67 \
(msg:"Kali Linux Boot Detected"; \
content:"kali"; nocase; \
sid:1000005; rev:1;)
```

---

# Rule 6

## Gmail Access

```snort
alert tcp $HOME_NET any -> any 80 \
(msg:"GMAIL Access"; \
content:"gmail"; nocase; \
sid:1000006; rev:1;)
```

---

# Rule 7

## Facebook Access

```snort
alert tcp $HOME_NET any -> any 80 \
(msg:"FACEBOOK Access"; \
content:"facebook"; nocase; \
sid:1000007; rev:1;)
```

---

# Rule 8

## Instagram Access

```snort
alert tcp $HOME_NET any -> any 80 \
(msg:"INSTAGRAM Access"; \
content:"instagram"; nocase; \
sid:1000008; rev:1;)
```

Save.

---

# 7. Test Configuration

```bash
sudo snort -T -c /etc/snort/snort.conf
```

Expected:

```text
Snort successfully validated the configuration
```

---

# 8. Start Snort IDS

```bash
sudo snort -A console \
-i ens33 \
-c /etc/snort/snort.conf
```

Replace:

```text
ens33
```

with your interface.

